where did the phrase a dime a dozen originate the same place we got the old classifications for sizes of nails something that was 'a dime a dozen' could be found at a general store for ten cents a dozen hence the phrase nails used to be classified as 'three penny ' 'ten penny ' etc the larger the number the smaller the nail this comes from the number of nails that could be bought for a penny three penny nails were three for a penny you get the picture Nail (engineering) United States dollar Dime novel Pound sterling Duodecimal Dime (U.S. coin) English plural Penny (U.S. coin) English unit United States Mint ITunes Music Store Fischer Random Chess Money in Harry Potter Planet Defensive team Legal tender Make money fast Paintball Tin whistle Hornbostel-Sachs Irish pound CPU cache Australian dollar Brush Shilling Motion picture rating system Dollar store Hersheypark March of Dimes Digital photography Gambling Fuse (electrical) Slot machine RISC Jamaican dollar Farthing (coin) Good Times Fuel tax Frank Woolworth 10 (number) Coin Coalition Coinage of the Republic of Ireland British coin Florin Directive 67/548/EEC Mail Numerology Penny Black Ballpoint pen British coinage Dewey Decimal Classification Bunnings Warehouse Donald Duck McCrory Stores Mill (currency) Double Nickels on the Dime Compendium of postage stamp issuers (Sm - So) British Fifty Pence coin Loafers Coin CPU design Upholstery Compendium of postage stamp issuers (Gh - Gz) Esperanto grammar Compendium of postage stamp issuers (Na - Ni) Painter and decorator Burial Hard disk United States dollar coin Erastus Corning Normal distribution Compendium of postage stamp issuers (Ni - Nz) Cent (currency) Psychological pricing Coin collecting Memory Stick The Jetsons Stoma Scientific classification The Beatles discography Joke Compendium of postage stamp issuers (To - Tz) Steven Wright Asian Elephant Chris Pennie Pricing Password Macro photography Steve Martin Compendium of postage stamp issuers (Brit - British) Curre